<br>
"Have I proc'ed?"<br>
"Am I proc'ing?"<br>
"Am I going to proc?"<br>
<br>
That makes the proc system stateful. Some state of a weapon's proc status must be stored at all times. I can't think of any other system in the EQ combat engine that is stateful in the same regard, and I find it unlikely that something like proc'ing would warrant such a complex logic system when dramatically more game-impacting systems operate without logic at all. <br>
<br>
That being said...<br>
<br>
I do not doubt that the parses from the Shaman board are correct. However, there is more than one conclusion that can be drawn from them... One is that a given weapon has a specified interval during which, on average, it will always proc a certain number of times. I find this unlikely due to the reasons stated above.<br>
<br>
The other conclusion is that a given weapon has a specified proc rate that is a percentage chance to proc on every swing, AND <b>the fundamental mechanism behind the concept of slowing a PC or an NPC is not what we've always assumed it to be.</b><br>
<br>
The assumption about slow by most folks (myself included) is that slow simply reduces by a percentage the of times your weapons swing over a given period of time. The second conclusion drawn from the Shaman board data says differently. It implies that a slow does not alter how often your weapons swing, but rather reduces the number of swings that are passed from the combat engine into practical combat, and any round that passes a proc check is passed back automatically. (Or, at least, the proc is passed back)<br>
<br>
Thus, with a 50% slow, you're still attacking at 100%, but only every other swing is actually being applied towards the fight, giving the functional impression of attacking 50% more slowly. With an 80% slow, only every fifth swing is being passed back. Any time a swing procs, it bypasses the slow and is passed back.<br>
<br>
It would be interesting to see a similar test done with Haste.<br>
<br>
Do I know this to be a fact? No.<br>
<br>
Do I have any evidence to support it? No.<br>
<br>
Am I personally even convinced it's true? No.<br>
<br>
Is it a very reasonable and possible explination? Absolutely.<br>
<br>
Yaen B`zhen<br>
Overlord of the Lightbearer<br>
Povar<br>
